recordings.loc: Waterton Lakes National Park, Alberta
recordings.rmk:
This was previously an unidentified VIREO.  Discussions with others has narrowed the vocalization down to either Red-eyed Vireo or Philadelphia Vireo.   Visual markers indicate that this was a Philadelphia Vireo.  Visual description below: 

Two of us observed it.  It had yellow underparts but there could have been some amount of yellow light reflected from the aspen leaves so I am a bit cautious about that conclusion.  However, it had a distinct eyebrow but not a red eye.  Philadelphia Vireo would be well out of its known range here, but not habitat.  It is not unheard of to have "boreal" breeding species  along the front of the Rocky Mtns and well to the south. 

Aspen leaves rustling in the wind.  Some highway traffic.

recordings.file-name: XC293942-Zamorano campus 6dec2015 by O Komar Philadelphia vireo alarm call MVI_2517.mp3
recordings.rmk: This bird was agitated because of a vocalizing Glaucidium (pygmy-owl) in the same tree. I briefly observed a very agitated, pale, apparent juvenile (due to paleness) vireo that was probably the bird recorded. Plumage was consistent with V. philadelphicus but identification was based on reference recordings of the alarm call.  Recording was made from a video recorded on a digital camera (Canon Powershot SX50) and transferred to MP3 via ZamZar.com online service.

recordings.loc: Powderhorn Park, Minneapolis, Hennepin, Minnesota
recordings.rmk:
Pretty terrible recording, but possibly interesting nonetheless.  

A migrant bird foraging in Ash and *Ostrya virginiana* on wooded hillside in an urban park.  Offered very close views, but stayed entirely silent for nearly the entire 45 minutes that I watched it.  Eventually I tried to solicit some vocalizations with playback (using XC22433), and it immediately flew in very close to me (2-3m away on a branch just above eye level), fluttered its wings rapidly against its body while looking around anxiously to find the source of the sound, and gave these little *pip-pip-pip* calls.  Sex unknown.
